com.pb.sawdust.tabledata

Class AbstractTableIndex<I,K>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.pb.sawdust.tabledata.AbstractTableIndex<I,K>
  • Type Parameters:
    I - The type of the table index components.
    K - The type of the key used to uniquely map a group of index components.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    TableIndex<I>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    BasicTableIndex, DigestTableIndex, SimpleTableIndex

    public abstract class AbstractTableIndex<I,K>
extends java.lang.Object
implements TableIndex<I>
    The AbstractTableIndex class provides a skeletal version of TableIndex which reduces the coding burden on the implementing user. It actually implements all of the methods from TableIndex, leaving it to the implementing class to define how a unique key is built from a series of index values. This class contains two type parameters, one, K, for the type of key that the buildIndexKey(I ...) returns, and a second, I, which is equivalent to TableIndex's type parameter, and indicates the types of the index columns. A reference to the data table this index refers to is held by this class and is explicitly used with the buildIndex() method.

    • Method Detail

      • buildIndexKey

        protected abstract K buildIndexKey(I... indexValues)
        Build the key from the provided index values. For each unique set of index values, the returned key must be unique; identical keys should only be returned when all index values, in order, are identical. Equality is determined in the manner that key matches are defined in the java.lang.Map<K,V> interface (key1 equals key2 if (key1==null ? key2==null : key1.equals(key2))).

        Efficiency gains can be achieved by developing a more efficient key-building algorithm, and if equality checks (i.e. the .equals(Object) method and hash lookups) are as efficient as possible.

        Parameters:
        indexValues - The values to build the index key from.
        Returns:
        the index key.

      • buildIndex

        public void buildIndex()
        Description copied from interface: TableIndex
        Build the index. Calling this method should update both the index's row number mapping as well as the array returned by TableIndex.getUniqueValues(). This method need not be called upon object creation; that is, there is no expectation that implementing classes should build the index when constructed. There is also no expectation that an index should be rebuilt after every data table update; an index is only consistent with its corresponding data table so long as that data table has not be altered (and the index not rebuilt).
        Specified by:
        buildIndex in interface TableIndex<I>

        public java.util.Set<java.lang.Integer> getRowNumbers(I... indexValues)
        Description copied from interface: TableIndex
        Get the row numbers corresponding to a given set of index values. The index column values must be provided in the same order as returned by TableIndex.getIndexColumnLabels(). If no rows are found corresponding to the index values, an exception is thrown (as opposed to returning an empty set, which could mask errors). The row numbers returned will correspond to the order of the source data table when the index was last built.
